    <h2 id="bike-bus-beacon-instructions">Bike Bus Beacon Instructions</h2>
    <p>When you&#39;re (physically) within the map area, you can test the beacon by going to the link below on your phone. Before you click that link, please read all of these instructions:</p>
    <p>When you open the beacon link, your device should prompt you to share your location with the website. Make sure you say yes, or the beacon won&#39;t be able to track you. From then on, whenever the beacon web page is visible on your phone screen, a dot will show up on the tracker map showing your location.</p>
    <p>Some beacon tips:</p>
      <h3>Setup</h3>
        <p>
          <em style="color:red;">The beacon will only track you when it&#39;s visible on screen.</em>
      </p>
            <p>
              Set your phone not to automatically go to sleep or dim the screen. On an iPhone, that&#39;s in Settings under <strong>Display and Brightness</strong> &gt; <strong>Auto-Lock</strong>.</p>
          
                <p>Mounting the phone running the beacon on your bike with a phone mount is a great way to ensure that the screen is always on. It also helps you keep the bus on schedule if you&#39;re up front.</p>
    <p>Make sure your phone is well-charged.</p>
      <h3>
        The Tracker Link
      </h3>
        <p>Don&#39;t dox yourself! Don&#39;t run the beacon until you&#39;re away from home, ideally at the starting point of the bus. If you do test the beacon at home, turn off the beacon as soon you&#39;re done to erase your location.</p>
    <p>Since anyone who opens the beacon url will update the tracker, I recommend not distributing it widely (or at all) beyond the person who will be running it. For example, we&#39;ve had the link posted in our slack and people will occasionally get curious and run it by accident. Now I just DM it to the driver the day before the bus.</p>
    <p>If the link is ever compromised, let me know and I&#39;ll change it.</p>
      <h3>
        The Ride
      </h3>            
    <p>The tracker will be most accurate if the person running the beacon is riding at the front of the bus.</p>
